[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "When the Jews laid wait for him . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—In sailing for Syria, Cenchreæ would naturally be the port of embarkation, and St. Paul’s presence there may reasonably be connected with the mention of Phœbe, the deaconess of that church, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 16:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". His intention was, however, frustrated. The malignant Jews of Corinth watched their opportunity. At Cenchreæ, amid the stir and bustle of a port, they might do what they had failed to do before. Here there was no Gallio to curb their fury, and throw the ægis of his tolerant equity over their victim. Their plans were laid, and their victim was to be seized and made away with as he was on the point of embarking. On hearing of the plot, the Apostle had to change his plans, and started with his companions for Macedonia, either travelling by land or taking a ship bound for one of its ports, instead of the one bound for Cæsarea, or Tyre, or Joppa. It is clear that the latter course would have baffled his murderers quite as much as the former.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 20:3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 20:3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And there ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Namely, in Greece; he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "abode three months ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Meeting, it seems, with business there as he often did in other places, which detained him longer than he expected. During this time, he received from the churches of Achaia the money which they had collected for the saints in Judea, agreeably to his direction to the Corinthians, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 16:1-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". At this time also he wrote his epistle to the Romans, of whose affairs he had heard by Aquila and Priscilla. For, it plainly appears, that epistle was written before his imprisonment at Rome; and in it he speaks of a collection made by the churches of Macedonia and Achaia, with which he was hastening to Jerusalem, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:25-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; a circumstance which fixes it to this time. It appears, also, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 16:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that Timothy and Sosipater (or Sopater, one of the noble Bereans) were with him when that epistle was written, which agrees with verse four of this chapter, by which we find they both attended him into Asia. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when the Jews had laid wait for him, as he was about to sail into Syria, he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Upon this account; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "purposed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Εγενετο γνωμη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the thought, or design, occurred, or he conceived the intention; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to return through Macedonia ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The fact seems to be, that having finished all his matters in Greece, he had proposed to sail directly into Syria. But the Jews, who had heard of the money he was carrying to Jerusalem; and who, besides, hated him as an enemy to their religion, lying in wait for him in Cenchrea, the eastern port of Corinth, where he was to embark, he changed his resolution. So that avoiding that port, which was about nine miles from Corinth, he returned by land, through Macedonia, in such time that he left Philippi after the days of unleavened bread, and so began his voyage into Syria.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "20:1-6 Tumults or opposition may constrain a Christian to remove from his station or alter his purpose, but his work and his pleasure will be the same, wherever he goes. Paul thought it worth while to bestow five days in going to Troas, though it was but for seven days' stay there; but he knew, and so should we, how to redeem even journeying time, and to make it turn to some good account.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And there abode - Why he remained here is unknown. It is probable that while in Greece he wrote the Epistle to the Romans. Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:25-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And when the Jews laid wait for him - There was a design formed against him by the Jews, which they sought to execute. Why they formed this purpose the historian has not informed us.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As he was about to sail - It would seem from this, that the design of the Jews was to attack the ship in which he was about to sail, or to arrest him on shipboard. This fact determined him to take a much more circuitous route by land, so that the churches of Macedonia were favored with another visit from him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Into Syria - On his way to Jerusalem.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He purposed ... - He resolved to avoid the snare which they had laid for him, and to return by the same way in which he had come into Greece. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "He purposed ... - He resolved to avoid the snare which they had laid for him, and to return by the same way in which he had come into Greece. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3. And there abode three months—Though the province only is here mentioned, it is the city of Corinth that is meant, as the province of \"Macedonia\" (Ac 20:1) meant the city of Philippi. Some rough work he anticipated on his arrival at Corinth (2Co 10:1-8, 11; 13:1-10) though he had reason to expect satisfaction on the whole; and as we know there were other churches in Achaia besides that at Corinth (2Co 1:1; 11:10), he would have time enough to pay them all a brief visit during the three months of his stay there. This period was rendered further memorable by the despatch of the Epistle to the Romans, written during his stay at Corinth and sent by \"Phœbe, a servant [deaconess] of the Church at Cenchrea\" (see on [2068]Ac 18:3), a lady apparently of some standing and substance, who was going thither on private business. (See on [2069]Ro 16:1 and see [2070]Introduction to Romans).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And when the Jews laid wait for him, as he was about to sail into Syria—He had intended to embark, probably at Cenchrea, the eastern harbor of the city, for Palestine, on his route to Jerusalem, the third part of his plan (Ac 19:21). But having detected some conspiracy against his life by his bitter Jewish enemies as at Damascus (Ac 9:22-25) and Jerusalem (Ac 9:29, 30), he changed his plan and determined \"to return\" as he had come, \"through Macedonia.\" As he was never more to return to Corinth, so this route would bring him, for the last time, face to face with the attached disciples of Berea, Thessalonica, and Philippi.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
